    <ReasonableCauseExplanation documentId="R000004" softwareId="22015720" softwareVersionNum="v1.00">
      <ExplanationTxt>When we changed our fiscal year, we filed 990-N for the original fiscal year, ending June 30, 2022. We also filed 990-EZ for the new fiscal year, which began January 2022. So the first 6 months of 2022 were covered by both filings. On Sept 18, 2023, we were issued a Failure to File notice (CP259A) for the tax period ending Dec 31, 2022. On Oct 4, I spoke to an IRS agent who released us from the notification list and assured us that we did not have to file the indicated return, since we already filed for the calendar year. But another CP259A was issued on Nov 13 for the same issue. On speaking to an agent in response to the second notice, I was informed that we would be required to file 990-EZ covering just July 1 - Dec 31, 2022, since the first half of the year was already covered by our previous 990-N. So technically we did not file late. We filed on time, but we simply did not know that we were filing in the wrong way. This filing should correct that misunderstanding.</ExplanationTxt>
    </ReasonableCauseExplanation>
